<bibRefCitation id="866A23670919511EBAEBF664C5CDF454" author="Spencer, KA" journalOrPublisher="Agriculture Handbook" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1 - 478" publicationUrl="https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/51258090" refId="B261" refString="Spencer, KA, Steyskal, GC, 1986b. Manual of the Agromyzidae (Diptera) of the United States. U.S.D.A. Agriculture Handbook 638: 1 - 478, https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/51258090" title="Manual of the Agromyzidae (Diptera) of the United States. U. S. D. A." url="https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/51258090" volume="638" year="1986 b">Spencer and Steyskal 1986b</bibRefCitation>
[as synonym of 
<taxonomicName id="0EAB437C2D083BAE0ACBCB602A85EC1A" family="Phytomyzinae" genus="Cephyalomyza" higherTaxonomySource="treatment-meta" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cephyalomyza" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="genus">Cephyalomyza</taxonomicName>
]. 
<bibRefCitation id="2536736324C3D0A4421BD887DD99B8A6" author="Spencer, KA" editor="McAlpine, JF" journalOrPublisher="2). Monograph 28, Research branch, Agriculture Canada, Ottawa" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="869 - 879" refId="B255" refString="Spencer, KA, 1987. Agromyzidae. In: McAlpine, JF, Ed., Manual of Nearctic Diptera (Vol. 2). Monograph 28, Research branch, Agriculture Canada, Ottawa: 869 - 879" title="Agromyzidae." volumeTitle="Manual of Nearctic Diptera (Vol." year="1987">Spencer 1987</bibRefCitation>
: 877 [as valid subgenus].
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="4D018202C054A840CE291CB839648D1F" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="note">
<paragraph id="654A545F47192FF468D82D7A69EEA4CE" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName id="B9A60B6D649FC85C3E4E9EFD856E326D" authorityName="Hendel" authorityYear="1931" class="Insecta" family="Phytomyzinae" genus="Amauromyza" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Amauromyza" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="71DCC1D75D2A4C8F2DAA9CFE225D2D3E" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Amauromyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a morphologically diverse genus of at least 60 species. 
<bibRefCitation id="07F2903A45E2725C688CBFED980B6666" DOI="https://doi.org/10.4039/tce.2012.80" author="Boucher, S" journalOrPublisher="The Canadian Entomologist" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="733 - 757" refId="B15" refString="Boucher, S, 2012b. Revision of the Canadian species of Amauromyza Hendel (Diptera: Agromyzidae). The Canadian Entomologist 144: 733 - 757, DOI: https://doi.org/10.4039/tce.2012.80" title="Revision of the Canadian species of Amauromyza Hendel (Diptera: Agromyzidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.4039/tce.2012.80" volume="144" year="2012 b">Boucher (2012b)</bibRefCitation>
provided the most recent treatment of the genus, revising the Canadian fauna and providing a list of world species. The genus is defined entirely by male genitalic characters, making it difficult to identify externally, although many species have a very high gena that can be&gt; 1/3-1/2 the height of the eye (as in 
<taxonomicName id="2825C2B901A6D18164EDAFE08A8B9243" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="A." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="A. karli" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="karli">
<emphasis id="5E993ED2516FD52B611FF2B715EB13D5" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">A. karli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), and all Delmarva species have four scattered rows of acrostichal setulae, no acrostichal setae, four dorsocentrals (the presutural seta is sometimes absent in species found elsewhere), erect to reclinate orbital setulae (proclinate or no setulae occur in a minority of species elsewhere), a weakly sclerotised frons that buckles anteriorly in preserved specimens, a costa that extends to vein M1 (to R4+5 in two European species), and a dark, heavily pigmented distiphallus that is surrounded by a spinulose membrane. Compounding this difficulty in identification, the most diagnostic character of the genus, a sclerotised, bowl-shaped sperm pump, is also found in some 
<taxonomicName id="5F37E1B421FBC3E71200959B3E7C22F6" authorityName="Frey" authorityYear="1946" class="Insecta" family="Phytomyzinae" genus="Nemorimyza" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Nemorimyza" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="462076053C824A10824B76515C2AC490" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Nemorimyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="E8403CAA1DB8E9AB19705C0EDDD82876" authorityName="Mik" authorityYear="1894" class="Insecta" family="Phytomyzinae" genus="Liriomyza" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Liriomyza" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="0A821A6F8AB0A3FECC7008261D6BB912" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Liriomyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="8EEAC1C34B74F990B0EE77435BBAB8DC" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Agromyzinae">Agromyzinae</taxonomicName>
. A stout, semi-circular hypandrium is also characteristic, but this character is also found infrequently elsewhere in the subfamily. Previously, those phytomyzine species with a dark or spotted halter could be quickly assigned to the genus, but 
<bibRefCitation id="8FB68091D24F71C2361D126692C5BF8A" author="Zlobin, VV" journalOrPublisher="An International Journal of Dipterological Research" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="271 - 280" refId="B305" refString="Zlobin, VV, 1996. The genus Amauromyza Hendel (Diptera, Agromyzidae): a clarification of species of the subgenus Annimyzella Spencer. An International Journal of Dipterological Research 7 (4): 271 - 280" title="The genus Amauromyza Hendel (Diptera, Agromyzidae): a clarification of species of the subgenus Annimyzella Spencer." volume="7" year="1996">Zlobin (1996)</bibRefCitation>
produced a more thorough definition of 
<taxonomicName id="88C27CE251666845A6A2AE7273F63F0A" authorityName="Hendel" authorityYear="1931" class="Insecta" family="Phytomyzinae" genus="Amauromyza" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Amauromyza" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="F1324DE709BCB77E98A4D6F3B6E18F59" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Amauromyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and discovered that this character was paralleled elsewhere, albeit uncommonly.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A1152A5E84192D3FCA34CDE4E9A28137" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Three subgenera were recognised as occurring in the Nearctic by 
<bibRefCitation id="229505E258E47931AD12325F6A749ED6" author="Spencer, KA" journalOrPublisher="Agriculture Handbook" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1 - 478" publicationUrl="https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/51258090" refId="B261" refString="Spencer, KA, Steyskal, GC, 1986b. Manual of the Agromyzidae (Diptera) of the United States. U.S.D.A. Agriculture Handbook 638: 1 - 478, https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/51258090" title="Manual of the Agromyzidae (Diptera) of the United States. U. S. D. A." url="https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/51258090" volume="638" year="1986 b">Spencer and Steyskal (1986b)</bibRefCitation>
: 
<taxonomicName id="5FF651FEA6C24FCF6EEF739CA6362E7E" authority="Hendel, 1931" authorityName="Hendel" authorityYear="1931" class="Insecta" family="Phytomyzinae" genus="Cephalomyza" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cephalomyza" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="9A753097E50EA6DF32B49086BD25AB1C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Cephalomyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Hendel, 
<taxonomicName id="E4E845DAEBE24746D9D2B05017238CCD" authorityName="Spencer" authorityYear="1977" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Catalpomyza" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Catalpomyza" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="94C49F0841B76C3C7931D176BC42EB1C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Catalpomyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Spencer and 
<taxonomicName id="9181278D3A79CE870E6577387D4A4A26" authority="Spencer, 1981" authorityName="Spencer" authorityYear="1981" class="Insecta" family="Phytomyzinae" genus="Annimyzella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Annimyzella" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="9D3488A4E4C5B979CCBE7EFCB03BE486" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Annimyzella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Spencer (now a synonym of 
<taxonomicName id="3622EE83D88DD3D4FB970CB4641D83B7" authorityName="Frey" authorityYear="1946" class="Insecta" family="Phytomyzinae" genus="Nemorimyza" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Nemorimyza" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="94E2FEED37CDEB4A1D8AC704F822E135" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Nemorimyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="F4000FF6B7B0DED84C718382784F8675" author="Zlobin, VV" journalOrPublisher="An International Journal of Dipterological Research" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="271 - 280" refId="B305" refString="Zlobin, VV, 1996. The genus Amauromyza Hendel (Diptera, Agromyzidae): a clarification of species of the subgenus Annimyzella Spencer. An International Journal of Dipterological Research 7 (4): 271 - 280" title="The genus Amauromyza Hendel (Diptera, Agromyzidae): a clarification of species of the subgenus Annimyzella Spencer." volume="7" year="1996">Zlobin 1996</bibRefCitation>
). A fourth subgenus, 
<taxonomicName id="E219E48677BD0B64F7A71A81C8E2F477" authority="" authorityName="Hendel" authorityYear="1931" class="Insecta" family="Phytomyzinae" genus="Trilobomyza" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Trilobomyza" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="8EB2ACD9598A2825ECE11AEF3D50CF8A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Trilobomyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Hendel, which contains the introduced and increasingly widespread 
<taxonomicName id="2AD87E2C4CC25AB2854DFB8417D72E09" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="A." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="A. flavifrons" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="flavifrons">
<emphasis id="E2F90DF59DEC626C5A5FA0D4E5832318" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">A. flavifrons</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, was included as a junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName id="F0B2244E1A37E5E83BBE2634CE2B1B3E" authority="Hendel, 1931" authorityName="Hendel" authorityYear="1931" class="Insecta" family="Phytomyzinae" genus="Cephalomyza" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cephalomyza" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="971BD643C142DE32783719634932818A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Cephalomyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, although 
<bibRefCitation id="E88EB7D94851DDFB97C01DDEFCB6F78B" author="Spencer, KA" editor="McAlpine, JF" journalOrPublisher="2). Monograph 28, Research branch, Agriculture Canada, Ottawa" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="869 - 879" refId="B255" refString="Spencer, KA, 1987. Agromyzidae. In: McAlpine, JF, Ed., Manual of Nearctic Diptera (Vol. 2). Monograph 28, Research branch, Agriculture Canada, Ottawa: 869 - 879" title="Agromyzidae." volumeTitle="Manual of Nearctic Diptera (Vol." year="1987">Spencer (1987)</bibRefCitation>
used it as valid only a year later. The nominal subgenus is restricted to the Old World. 
<bibRefCitation id="C123CC69F3A9C566B3C4A16776725F37" author="Zlobin, VV" journalOrPublisher="An International Journal of Dipterological Research" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="271 - 280" refId="B305" refString="Zlobin, VV, 1996. The genus Amauromyza Hendel (Diptera, Agromyzidae): a clarification of species of the subgenus Annimyzella Spencer. An International Journal of Dipterological Research 7 (4): 271 - 280" title="The genus Amauromyza Hendel (Diptera, Agromyzidae): a clarification of species of the subgenus Annimyzella Spencer." volume="7" year="1996">Zlobin (1996)</bibRefCitation>
stated that the validity of the subgenera was uncertain, and they are not considered in the present revision pending future study to determine whether or not they are both monophyletic and useful for diagnosis.
</paragraph>
